ican Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Italian: habitational name from Pella in Novara province.","Italian: possibly a shortened form of <i>Iacopella</i>, a pet form of the personal name <i>Iacopa</i>, feminine form of <i>Iacopo</i> (see   Jacob  ), or of <i>Filippella</i>, a pet form of <i>Filippa</i>, feminine form of   Filippo  .","possibly Catalan: from old Catalan <i>pella</i> ‘used clothes’, perhaps a nickname for someone poorly dressed."],"variants":[{"name":"Jacob","meanings":["Jewish, English, Welsh, German, Portuguese, French (mainly Alsace and Lorraine), Walloon, Breton, Dutch, Flemish, Swedish, Danish, and Norwegian: derivative, via Latin <i>Jacob(us)</i>, from the Hebrew personal name <i>Ya‘aqob</i> (<i>Yaakov</i>). In the Bible, this is the name of the crafty younger twin brother of Esau (Genesis 25:26), who took advantage of the latter's hunger and impetuousness to persuade him to part with his birthright ‘for a mess of potage’. The name is traditionally interpreted as coming from Hebrew <i>akev</i> ‘heel’: Jacob is said to have been born holding on to Esau's heel. In English usage the name <i>Jacob</i> is regarded as distinct from the name   James  , but they are of identical origin. In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed cognates from other languages, for example Assyrian/Chaldean or Arabic   Yaqub  ,   Yakub  ,   Yacoub  , or   Yacob  , Slovenian   Jakob   and <b>Jakop</b>, Czech and Slovak   Jakub  , and also their patronymics and other derivatives (see examples at   Jacobs   and   Jacobson  ). The name <i>Jacob</i> is also found among Christians in southern India (compare   Chacko  ), but since South Indians traditionally do not have hereditary surnames, the southern Indian name was in most cases registered as such only after immigration of its bearers to the US."]}]},{"name":"Marra","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo, Antonio, Rocco, Carmine, Salvatore, Enrico, Pasquale, Sal, Vincenzo, Alessandro, Gaetano, Marino.","Italian (southern): habitational name from any of the places so called in central and southern Italy, from <i>marra</i> ‘heap of stones’.","Italian, Galician, and Portuguese: from <i>marra</i> ‘hoe’, in Galician and Portuguese also ‘big mallet for breaking stones’ (from Latin <i>marra</i>), presumably a metonymic occupational name for one who made such implements or for one who used them."],"variants":[{"name":"Marrazzo","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Salvatore, Tobia, Carmine, Caterina, Cesare, Ciro, Dante, Domenic, Natale, Salvator, Saverio.","Italian:","probably from a pejorative form of   Marra  ."]},{"name":"Marro","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo, Carmine, Pasco, Carlo, Pasquale, Philomena, Pietro, Rinaldo, Sal, Salvatore, Savino.","Italian (southern): probably a masculine form of   Marra  .","Spanish: nickname from <i>marro</i> ‘ram’."]},{"name":"La Marra","meanings":["Italian (southern; also <b>Lamarra</b>): variant of   Marra  , with the definite article <i>la</i>."]},{"name":"Marre","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Jacques.","Italian: from the plural of <i>marra</i> (see   Marra  ).","French: nickname for a stubborn or narrow-minded man, from Old French <i>marre</i> ‘ram’."]},{"name":"Marrow","meanings":["English: nickname from Middle English <i>marwe</i>, <i>marowe</i> ‘companion, mate’."]}]},{"name":"Angelo","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Greek <i>angelos</i> ‘messenger (of God)’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Angelo Della Marra was born in 1172, in Naples, Campania, Italy. He had at least 2 sons with Sichelgaita Angelo della. He died in 1239, at the age of 67."},"et":{"1172–1239":"1172–1239","1177–Female":"1177–Surnud","1202–Male":"1202–Surnud","1238–1270":